post_text:
Dear 7-12 Parents/Guardians,

We wanted to touch base with you now that summer school is complete and we are working on finalizing grades and course completion for the 2019-2020 school year. Per the new policy adopted, for the fall and moving forward students needed to complete their courses during summer school to receive credit. If your child did not complete a class, they will only receive a semester credit and have the option to retake the second semester or just take the single semester credit. If it is a core class required for graduation, they will have to retake all of second semester. Remember, if a student has passed the summative assessments, they can move ahead quicker than the classroom teacher.

Please reach out via email to Mr. Ray or Mr. DeBruycker with any questions.

post_text:
Dear 7-12 Students,

Many of you have reached out about summer school and the possibility of continuing summer school with the remote learning format. Due to the situations of COVID-19 the district has decided to make this an option for you with some restrictions.

1.) All communication will be through Ms. Buswell and she will relay all work to the appropriate teacher.
2.) The class will need to be completed by July 9th, the last day of summer school.
3.) Any test will need to be taken in person.
4.) All work is still required to be done for course completion.

The district still feels the best option is to attend summer school in person but if you have concerns or conflicts this is another option for you.

Summer school runs June 15th - July 9th. Monday - Thursday 8am - 12 pm. This gives you 16 days of in person help to finish up classes.

Thank you
Mr. Ray
Mr. DeBruycker

A special thank you to all of the candidates for running for the two vacant school board trustee positions. Unofficial results for the CPS School Board of Trustees race are as follows:

*Ronald Barnhill Jr. - 250
*Susan Bender - 160
*David Freebury - 178
*Meagan Heinen - 559
*Anna Walter - 686

A BIG thank you to Kody Farkell and the Clerk and Recorder's Office and our Election Judges.

The Conrad Junior High and High School WIT Team (whatever it takes to be kind) is urging Conrad residents to take part April 6-10th!

There are many benefits of this bear hunt:
1) People are connecting a safe way!
2) Getting out and getting active!
3) Spending time with family!
4) It can be done by all ages, not just K-12!

If you put a bear in your window, take a picture and let us know.
If you are on a walk - count your bears and take a pic of your family on the bear hunt.

All pictures can be uploaded here to our facebook post!

Breakout Boxes were fun and challenging games in our after school programs. We miss having the kids work together in the library, but we were able to create an online class for students to break out of a digital box at home!!

post_text:
This afternoon, Governor Bullock declared a Stay at Home/Shelter in Place order for the state of Montana. This declaration is to begin at 12:01 AM Saturday. Conrad Public Schools opened up a last minute pickup time Thursday afternoon from 4:25 - 6:00 PM in anticipation of this order. A vast majority of our students and parents were able to adjust to utilize this time. With this success, the original pickup time scheduled for Friday 7:15 - 9:00 AM has been cancelled. CPS will arrange individually for any materials that were unable to be picked up. All other school off-site services including Grab and Go meals will continue. Thank you for your action and patience as we navigate through these uncertain times.

Sean Beddow, Superintendent
Conrad Public Schools

Please see the governor's statement at www.conradschools.org

As a district, we will provide 'brown bags' for breakfast and lunch items for any family who opts in to this service. There will not be a daily order form for meals, it will be opt in for the entirety of the closure.

All meals are free of charge!

To opt in, please complete the form below in its entirety.

-> If you want meals starting tomorrow Tuesday, 3/17, please let us know by 7pm via this form today, Monday, 3/16.

-> If you want ongoing meals beginning Wednesday, 3/18, complete this survey by 7pm as of Tuesday, 3/17.

Pick up for meals will be from 7:00am - 9:30am, Tuesday March 17 - Friday, March 27

Pick-up will be at the North Door of the Meadowlark Kitchen on the Elementary Playground. Please knock on the door when you arrive.

post_text: Per executive order of Governor Bullock, all of Conrad Public Schools will be closed for the next 2 weeks, Monday March 16 - Friday, March 27. A formal release will be posted shortly. Conrad Public Schools and the Pondera County Health Department are asking for the assistance of any student/family enrolled in CPS. If you have traveled outside of the immediate vicinity of Pondera County over the last 2 weeks, please complete the online survey requesting travel information. This will help us properly screen any travelers and to do everything we can to continue education in a safe and healthy manner. Either the school or the county health department will contact any students and their families if they believe any interventions are necessary to prevent the spread of COVID-19. Thank you for doing your part to help keep our community safe.

Smiles Across Montana (SAM) is a dental hygiene program that focuses on dental disease prevention. Our
services are provided at your child‚Äôs school and there is no fee to the child or family for our services. Below you will find the information and consent forms for your child. If you wish to participate in this program, please fill out the forms and return to your child's school by March 16th.

Meadowlark and Utterback will be sending home paper copies. Forms will be available for pick up at the CHS office.

Screening Dates Are:
Meadowlark - March 23
Utterback - March 24
CJSHS - March 25

At approximately 1:35 pm, Conrad Public Schools received instruction from the Conrad Police Department to lock down as a precaution. At no time were any of our students in danger. Lock down was released at 1:51pm. We will continue to work with local officials to ensure the safety of our students.

2:53 - As of this time, we have not received any information other than this was an outside threat, where our students were never in any danger. This was a proactive precautionary measure.
